Obesity, which poses a grave threat to humankind, has become one of the most important chronic diseases. By 2016, more than 1.9 billion adults over 18 years of age were overweight worldwide, of whom more than 650 million were obese (
 Chandramouli et al., 2019). Obesity has become an increasing concern because it is a major risk factor for diseases including cardiovascular disease, hypertension, dyslipidemia, diabetes, and cancer (
 Lopez et al., 2006; 
 Renehan et al., 2008; 
 Aune et al., 2016).
